statement of interest:
As an avid lover of mathematics, I have always been mesmerized by both the beauty of math but also the potential in its applications. Growing up, my father always told me that everything in our universe ‚Äî whether it be the plants around us or the stars in the sky ‚Äî could all be described using mathematics. When I was young, I didn't truly comprehend the meaning behind his words, but with the passing of time, I began to dive deeper into the art of problem-solving. Soon, I developed a deepened love and appreciation for perhaps the most simple yet complicated language in the world: the language of mathematics. A short equation, a simple model, from Euler's Formula to the Gold Ratio, mathematics has the power to say so much in so little.

Yet over time, I began to be captivated by the infinite applications and possibilities of math. Needless to say, math on its own is a beauty to behold, but when combined with other subjects like physics and biology, it has the power to change the world. My undeniable passion and solid foundation in mathematics greatly strengthen my qualifications as a candidate for COSMOS as math serves as the cornerstone for so many other fields of STEM.

My qualifications expand beyond my capabilities in terms of math and STEM ‚Äî my strong communication and presentation skills will empower me to draw the entire community of my cluster closer together. My experience on my high school speech team has guided me to find my voice and uncover my confidence. This year, I placed first in Declamation at National Catholic Forensic League Qualifications. Even though the program will be held virtually this year, I know that my outgoing and optimistic personality will enhance the experience of everyone in my cluster.

cluster 2: 

Genetics. The power and beauty of this word were truly introduced to me in my freshman year. A biology project on DNA sent me looking deeper and deeper into the complex and intricate world of genetics. While researching for the project, I could not help but look beyond the functionality of the different types of DNA, RNA, and enzymes, and instead, focus on why and how they do what they do. When I ran a lab for extracting DNA in a college-level laboratory because of the project, I was captivated by the environment and by each step of the procedure. Genetics and DNA ‚Äî what makes each of us so unique yet so similar ‚Äî has been a pronounced interest of mine ever since the project.
Yet the more I learn about genetics, the more I realize that there is still so much more knowledge out there awaiting my arrival. So many questions to answer, so many mysteries to solve, the unknown is always more mesmerizing than the known. And COSMOS is the best way for me to reach out beyond what I currently know and truly enhance my knowledge on a topic that I have a burning passion for.

I have been searching,
In agony, for the perfect poem.
A poem that says it all ‚Äî 
All my sorrows, all my joys.
The words that paint the picture
None but my heart can see.
A poem that lives, that reaches,
Beyond what I can.

But I never seem to see,
The destination of my journey.
Always out of reach, always out of touch.
I extend my hand,
Only to catch empty feathers. 
The words I cast, the paint that drops,
Everything falls into the wrong spot.

But can you see,
My toilsome search, 
For that of which I may never uncover. 
An undying want,
To rip open my heart for the world to see.
Yet what would it see?
My tears, my laughter? 
The words time has taken away ‚Äî
Or what it has failed to steal?

Perhaps this journey,
This endless, beautiful journey,
Is my poem.
My struggles the words, my love the paint,
Perfection woven only in imperfection.
My tainted life, my perfect poem.
